        Things were bad, and were getting worse the further we dug.  Dave and I could have worn signs around our necks that said "Designated tools of due diligence".  You can make the joke.<br/><br/>Here we were being brought into an organization because of some missing data, some employees being followed, and key members of staff possibly jumping ship to a competitor.  What could it all mean?<br/><br/>I took a gamble with my next move.  This game is all instict, and I've never found my gut to be wrong on matters like this.  I grabbed my case notes and walked to Mr. Jones' office in legal.  <br/><br/>Time to apply pressure to this gaping chest wound of a case.I spread page after page after page of case notes out in front of me on Jones' desk.  I asked some rather pointed questions, but my gut was telling me that Jones really didn't have a clue.  It looked like I'd have to show my hand in this card game.<br/><br/>"Mr. Jones, are you aware that VonHeffer and certain other executives in this company have been defrauding your investors from the very beginning?"  I asked.<br/><br/>"What do you mean?" Jones asked, looking like I was pusing bamboo chutes down under his fingernails.<br/><br/>"I have two sets of accounting records here.  One set is the set that you used to file all of your financial reports.  The information I gathered from these reports matches your public disclosures." I said.  "However, this other set of records tells a very different story.   It would appear that VonHeffer and crew have been treating themselves to large cash bonuses, personal perks that were written off as expenses, and let's not even talk about the company's stock option plan." I said as I placed the documents in front of Jones.  <br/><br/>"How did you... find... where... what the..." Jones sputtered off.<br/><br/>I spent the next hour briefing Jones on what Dave and I had uncovered.  I was going to throw the matter into his hands, collect our check and run away from this case as fast as my shoes could take me.  <br/><br/>Mick Thomas caught on to the "questionable" accounting practices that VonHeffer and several other officers of the company practiced.  The CFO was a personal friend of VonHeffer and disappeared on vacation.  Thomas found the records, burned them to CDR media and escaped to TouchThemSoft as fast as he could.  The CDR's were his insurance against VonHeffer suing him from jumping ship.<br/><br/>Thomas and the EA were indeed having an at-work affair.  Thomas had given the EA a copy of the CDR as insurance.  When Thomas found out that VonHeffer was on to him, Thomas and the EA staged the break-in at her place to explain the laptop (and the CDR) just "disappearing".  It was later discovered that the EA had saved hundreds of incriminating e-mails from VonHeffer as her own "insurance".  <br/><br/>VonHeffer's plan on bringing in an outside security investigation firm backfired in the worst way.  The forensic evidence that we were able to find, label, preserve and present aided an attorney that represented some of VonHeffer's largest investors.    Needless to say that VonHeffer and his cronies wound up with some jail time.  VonHeffer's company was bought by a much larger company and it's technology used in a much larger, more popular CRM solution.<br/><br/>Not every case goes smooth or even makes sense in the end - especially when things go badly.<br/><br/>(Aside)<br/>How did VonHeffer completely shoot himself in the foot?<br/><br/>Anyone want to take a guess at describing the entire scam that VonHeffer put together?  This casefile only highlights the very basics.<br/><br/>(/Aside)<br/><br/>Next time, new case file - and it's a weird one.<br/>
    </div>    
    <div class="spacer marginleftgutter">
            <hr/>
    <table width="100%" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" cellpadding="9px">
