                <div class="floatleft" style="margin-top:-2px; margin-right:10px"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111235054/http://it.toolbox.com/people/chiefmonkey/"><div class="userimage-defaulttiny" lazysource="http://userimages.ittoolbox.com/user/0/0/0/t_610000.jpg"></div></a>
</div>


<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111235054/http://it.toolbox.com/people/chiefmonkey/" class="size11">Chief Monkey</a>

<!---->

				
<span class="size11 darkgray">46 minutes ago</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">@pand0ra: Tricky questions.  In this particular case, I had to reason to suspect counsel was involved.  I can't say that's always been the case - but in this one, no reason.
<br>
<br>As far as going to LE, it really depends.  I have to sign a pretty hefty NDA just to get in the door of these places, and I have to concentrate on preserving the quality of the investigation.  Every case is different, but needless to say I have rarely gotten outside LE involved in the middle of an engagement w/o contacting my handlers first.   For obvious reasons, if I came upon something like a dead body or bomb making components, yes - I'd probably contact LE immediately.
<br>
<br>And yes, I'm walking around giving a direct answer to this.  Sorry.  :-(
<br>
<br>



</span>
		</div>
           
    <div class="spacer"></div>


